\subsection{Fit model}
\label{sec:fit_model}

The parameterizations of the signal and main background processes, as described in Sections~\ref{sec:sig_ttbar_pPb} and~\ref{sec:bkg_pPb} , respectively, 
are used to build a fit model that is applied to the data to extract the inclusive \ttbar\ cross section.  
The fit model predicts the total number of events in 1$\ell$4j0\cPqb, 1$\ell$4j1\cPqb, and 1$\ell$4j2\cPqb event categories by summing up the contributions
for \ttbar, and \PW+jets and \QCD\ multijet background, i.e., in each category (``k'') we write
\begin{equation}
N_\textrm{k}(\mjj)=N_\textrm{k}({\ttbar})\times \textrm{pdf}_\textrm{k}^{\ttbar}(\mjj)+N_\textrm{k}({\textrm{bkg}})\times \left( \textrm{pdf}_\textrm{k}^{\textrm{\PW+jets}}(\mjj)+f_\textrm{k}\times \textrm{pdf}_\textrm{k}^{\QCD}(\mjj)\right)\, ,
\label{eq:yields}
\end{equation}
where $N_\textrm{k}(i)$ ($\textrm{pdf}_\textrm{k}(i)$) is the total number of events (distribution) for the process $i$ in category c, 
and $f_\textrm{k}\in[0,1]$ is a parameter that regulates the relative contribution in background events from the \QCD\ multijet background;
$N_\textrm{k}({\QCD})= f_\textrm{k} N_\textrm{k}({\textrm{bkg}})$ is constrained by a Gaussian penalty term with mean and width as shown in Table~\ref{tab:qcdnorm}.
Given that the resolution and discrimination between the signal and background distributions of \mjj are superior with respect to the other mass variables, 
the fit used to extract the final cross section is performed with the \mjj variable. 
A variant of the nominal configuration included a two-dimensional fit to \mjj and $m_{\cPqt_{\textrm{had}}}$ variables; 
the \stt was found to be consistent with the one obtained from the \mjj fit, with the latter being described in the following. 

The number of \ttbar\ events in each category can be inferred based on multinomial probabilities to describe the expected number of signal events. 
Denoting by $\varepsilon_\cPqb$ the \cPqb-finding efficiency, i.e., the probability to select and tag a \cPqb quark from a top quark decay, one can write the following set of equations
for the number of signal events expected in each event category
\begin{equation}
N_{\mathrm{1\ell4j0b}}(\ttbar)= \varepsilon_\cPqb^2 N(\ttbar)~~~~
N_{\mathrm{1\ell4j1b}}(\ttbar)=2 \varepsilon_\cPqb (1-\varepsilon_\cPqb ) N(\ttbar)~~~~
N_{\mathrm{1\ell4j0b}}(\ttbar)=(1-\varepsilon_\cPqb )^2 N(\ttbar)\, .
\label{eq:sigyields}
\end{equation}
The parameter $\varepsilon_\cPqb$ is assigned 10\% pre-fit uncertainty by means of a Gaussian constraint. 
From simulation it is expected that $\varepsilon_\cPqb\approx 0.6$, a value which is consistent between the two final states, and \PYTHIA and \POWHEG MC samples. 
Imposing the relation in Eq.\,(\ref{eq:sigyields}) establishes the signal more accurately with respect to a fit where the signal yields would be left to float without 
any constraint in each category. Owing to the similarity of the distributions for wrongly assigned \ttbar\ events and the \PW+jets background, in particular,
in events with no \cPqb-tagged jets, the fit could be biased without the more refined signal model of Eq.\,(\ref{eq:sigyields}).

\subsection{Extraction of the inclusive \ttbar\ cross section}
\label{sec:xsection_pPb}

The final ingredient is the cross section which is used to parameterize $N(\ttbar)$ 
\begin{equation}
N(\ttbar)=\sigma_{\ttbar} A \varepsilon \mathcal{L}\, ,
\label{eq:xsec}
\end{equation}
where $A$ is the signal acceptance, $\varepsilon$ is the total lepton trigger and selection efficiency, and $\mathcal{L}$ is the total integrated luminosity. 
In the fit, these parameters float constrained by Gaussian penalty terms with mean and width corresponding to their estimated values and uncertainties, respectively.

In total 25 nuisance parameters are used: 12 background normalization-related parameters, six related to the distribution of the \PW+jets background (MPV and $\sigma$ of the Landau pdf), 
the \cPqb-finding efficiency, the JSF scaling factor, the integrated luminosity, and acceptance and efficiency values per final state. 
Out of the total nuisance parameters, 19 are associated with Gaussian constraints in the fit, i.e., only the total background yields are unconstrained.
As these parameters are not directly relevant to our measurement and reflect unknown degrees in the modeling of signal and background,
a profiling of the likelihood is performed in order to evaluate the uncertainty in the signal yield.

The likelihood is written as
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}(\sigma_{\ttbar},\vec{\Theta})=
\prod_k \mathcal{P} \left( N_k | \hat{N}_k(\stt,\theta_i) \right)\,
\prod_i \rho(\theta_i^0,\theta_i,\sigma_{\theta_i})\, ,
\label{eq:likelihood_pPb}
\end{equation}
where $\vec{\Theta}$ is the vector of nuisance parameters, $\theta_i^0$ and $\sigma_{\theta_i}$ are the mean and width of the Gaussian penalty term associated to the $i$th nuisance parameter
(when applicable), and the rest of the notations follow Eq.\,(\ref{eq:ll}). 
The constraint terms help to stabilize the fit, penalizing extreme values of the nuisance parameters that may be induced by the low event count in the data and 
the similarity for part of the signal with the background. 
The central value is thus obtained by maximizing Eq.\,(\ref{eq:likelihood_pPb}), and the associated uncertainty is determined after profiling the likelihood, i.e., by maximizing the test statistic
\begin{equation}
\lambda = \frac{\mathcal{L}(\stt,\hat{{\hat{{\vec{\Theta}}}}})}{\mathcal{L}({\hat{\sigma}_\mathrm{t\overline{t}}},\hat{\vec{\,\Theta}})}\, ,
\label{eq:profll_pPb}
\end{equation}
where the notations follow Eq.\,(\ref{eq:profll}).

Figure~\ref{fig:fitres} shows the \mjj distribution for events with zero, one, or at least two \cPqb-tagged jets, compared with the combined fit results. 
An excellent agreement is observed in all event categories between the data and the fitted signal and background parameterizations. 
The total number of signal events obtained through the combined fit to the $\mu$+jets and $\mathrm{e}$+jets final states is $710\pm130$. 
The  total  uncertainty  in the fitted signal events is obtained from the covariance matrix of the fit, and using Eq.\,(\ref{eq:xsec}) 
\begin{linenomath}
\begin{equation}
\stt=45\pm 8~(\textrm{total})~{\mathrm{nb}} \, .
\label{eq:xsection_pPb}
\end{equation}
\end{linenomath} 
The signal acceptance is determined from the \POWHEG NLO simulation (Table~\ref{tab:mc_pPb8TeV}) and is found to be $\mathcal{A} = 0.060 \pm 0.002$ and $0.056 \pm 0.002$  in 
the $\mu$+jets and $\mathrm{e}$+jets final states relative to all generated \ttbar\ events, 
including the branching fraction to leptons; the 4\% uncertainty in the acceptance correction includes its dependence on the proton and Pb PDFs, 
and on the values of theoretical scales and the \QCD\ coupling ($\alpha_{\textrm{s}} = 0.118 \pm 0.001$ at the \PZ\ boson pole mass).
The lepton trigger and selection efficiencies are $\varepsilon = 0.91 \pm 0.04$ and $0.63 \pm 0.03$ in the  $\mu$+jets and \Pe+jets as estimated from data.


Fitting exclusively the $\mu$+jets or $\mathrm{e}$+jets final state, the number of signal events is measured to be $420\pm80$ or $348\pm50$, and using Eq.\,(\ref{eq:xsec}) 
\begin{eqnarray}
\stt^{\mu+\textrm{jets}}=44\pm 3~(\stat)\pm 8~(\syst)~{\mathrm{nb}}\, ,\\ % \pm 6(\rm lumi)~{\rm nb}\,,\\
\stt^{\Pe+\textrm{jets}}=56\pm 4~(\stat)\pm 13~(\syst)~{\mathrm{nb}}\, ,% \pm 8(\rm lumi)~{\rm nb}\,,
\label{eq:xsection_pPb_perchannel}
\end{eqnarray}
where the uncertainty is further split into a statistical part, by leaving $\stt$ to float in the fit and fixing all other parameters to their post-fit values, 
and a systematic part, by subtracting the square of the statistical uncertainty from the square of the total uncertainty. 
Figure~\ref{fig:fitres} shows the \mjj distribution for events with zero, one, or at least two \cPqb-tagged jets, compared with the exclusive fit results.
The cross section is thus measured with a relative uncertainty of about 18 (23)\% in the $\mu$+jets ($\mathrm{e}$+jets) final state, and 17\% in their combination.

