\caption[Post-fit dijet invariant mass distributions in the $\mu$+jets, $\mathrm{e}$+jets, and combined $\ell$+jets final states at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,\TeV]{
  Invariant mass distributions of the \PW\ candidate, \mjj,
  in the 0 (a,\,d,\,g), 1 (b,\,e,\,h), and 2 (c,\,f,\,i) \cPqb{}-tagged jet categories after all selections in the $\ell$+jets (a--c), $\mu$+jets (d--f) and $\mathrm{e}$+jets (g--i) final states.
  The red and orange areas correspond to the signal simulation (correct and wrong assignments, respectively)
  while the blue one corresponds to the estimated non-top background contributions.
  The error bars indicate the statistical uncertainty~\citeTH{topobs_CMS_prl}.}
\label{fig:fitres}
\end{figure*}

The measured cross section is found to be consistent with the theoretical prediction~\cite{dEnterria:2017dum},
$\sigma(\pPb\to\ttbar + \mathrm{X}) = 59.0 \pm 5.3~(\textrm{PDF})\,^{+1.6}_{-2.1}~(\textrm{scale})~\mathrm{nb}$,
computed with \mcfm (v.8)~\cite{mcfm} using the CT14 proton PDF~\cite{Dulat:2015mca} and the EPPS16 nPDF for the lead
ions~\cite{EPPS16}, scaled to NNLO+NNLL accuracy with a $K$ factor computed with \textsc{Top++} (v.2.0)~\cite{top++}, 
and multiplied by $A = 208$.
The PDF uncertainties are obtained from the corresponding 56+40 eigenvalues of the CT14+EPPS16 sets
(corresponding to a 90\% confidence level) added in quadrature, while the theoretical scale uncertainty 
is estimated by modifying the factorization and renormalization scales within
a factor of two with respect to their default value set at $\mu_{\textrm{F}} = \mu_{\textrm{R}} = m_{\cPqt}$. 
The same calculation with the CT10 proton PDF~\cite{ct10} and EPS09~\cite{EPS09} nPDF yields 
$\sigma(\pPb\to\ttbar + \mathrm{X}) = 57.5 \pm \,^{+4.3}_{-3.3}(\textrm{PDF})\,^{+1.5}_{-2.0}~(\textrm{scale})~\mathrm{nb}$.
The difference in the theoretical \ttbar\ cross section computed with the PDF for free protons and for bound nucleons is small. A net overall 
antishadowing effect increases the total top-quark pair cross section by only 4\% for both the EPPS16 and EPS09 sets in \pPb relative to \pp collisions~\cite{dEnterria:2017dum}. 
Such a difference is too small to be observed in the data with the current experimental uncertainties.
Figure~\ref{fig:summary} shows the measured and
theoretical cross sections for \ttbar\ production in \pPb collisions at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,TeV, compared with the results from \pp
collisions at $\roots=8$\,\TeV~\cite{Khachatryan:2016mqs,Khachatryan:2016yzq} scaled by $A$ and by the ratio of 8.16 over 8\,\TeV\ NNLO+NNLL cross sections.

\begin{figure}[!ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/xsecsummary.pdf}
\caption[Inclusive \stt measurement in the $\mu$+jets, $\mathrm{e}$+jets, and combined $\ell$+jets final states at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,\TeV]{
Inclusive \ttbar\ cross section measurements in the $\mu$+jets, $\mathrm{e}$+jets, and combined $\ell$+jets final states using \pPb\ collisions at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,\TeV, 
compared to theoretical NNLO+NNLL predictions, and to scaled $\roots=8$\,\TeV pp results~\cite{Khachatryan:2016mqs,Khachatryan:2016yzq}. 
The total experimental error bars (theoretical error bands) include statistical and systematic (PDF and scale) uncertainties added in quadrature~\citeTH{topobs_CMS_prl}.}
\label{fig:summary}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Impact of the statistical and systematic uncertainties}
\label{sec:sig_ttbar}
The values obtained for the free parameters of the fit, i.e., the normalization of the signal,
\QCD\ multijet, and \PW+jets yields (as well as the parameters of their functional forms described
above), the b-finding efficiency, and the jet energy scale factor, are reported in Table~\ref{tab:nuisances}. 
It can be seen that the post-fit values for the \cPqb-finding and jet energy scale factor are close to their initial estimates, and are not significantly altered in the fit. 
Because of the low event count, the sensitivity of the fit to the \QCD\ multijet and \PW+jets background distributions is reduced, 
hence the fraction $f$ of \QCD\ multijet background is prone to statistical fluctuations. 
In the signal enriched categories, there is even lower sensitivity to the background parameters that is further reflected on the normalization, functional form, and relative contribution parameters. 
There is a fair agreement between the values obtained in the exclusive fits to the  in the $\mu$+jets (a--c) and $\mathrm{e}$+jets (d--f) final states, 
and obtained in the combined fit to all six event categories.

